    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-08-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-08-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="129" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d129">
                <head>No. 129.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Washburne</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                        the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-08-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 2, 1872</date>.
                                (Received August 15.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 671.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The National Assembly has substantially
                            completed its labors for the session, and has determined to adjourn over
                            from the 4th instant until the 11th of November. Mr. Thiers has greatly
                            strengthened himself in the country within the last few months, and it
                            may be said that he is now completely master of the situation. He goes
                            to Trouville, on the sea-shore, for a little rest, and after that it is
                            said that he will go to Fontainebleau, to remain until the assembly
                            shall reconvene.</p>
                <p>The success of the three-milliard loan is something astonishing. It has
                            been covered twelve times and a half, and the French people are very
                            much rejoiced.</p>
                <p>I have. &amp;c,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>E. B. WASHBURNE.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
